The College Football Playoff
----------------------------

Yesterday the College Football Playoff committee announced the four teams f=
or this years College Football Playoff (CFP): Michigan, Washington, Texas, =
and Alabama. It was, needless to say, a controversial choice.

To sum up the arguments briefly: Michigan and Washington were both undefeat=
ed in so-called =E2=80=9CPower 5=E2=80=9D conferences, i.e. the biggest fiv=
e conferences in college football; they were clearly in. The controversy wi=
th the final two selections arose from the fact that they weren=E2=80=99t t=
he only undefeated Power 5 conference champion: so was Florida State. Flori=
da State, though, lost its starting quarterback to a broken leg a couple of=
 weeks ago, which set up this decision. From The Athletic ( https://theathl=
etic.com/5108140/2023/12/03/college-football-playoff-florida-state-alabama/=
 ) :

In the final season of the four-team era =E2=80=94 before it expands to 12 =
in 2024 =E2=80=94 the CFP committee was charged with a very difficult decis=
ion that was guaranteed to result in a worthy team feeling cheated. The com=
mittee, for the first time, was actually going to have to choose what it va=
lues more =E2=80=94 the teams that earned it or the teams that look the bes=
t on TV.

Florida State, the most deserving, became the first unbeaten Power 5 confer=
ence champion left out of the field. The Seminoles were the ones left feeli=
ng cheated. And with that one decision, the committee didn=E2=80=99t just c=
hoose teams in a given year. It revealed to the world the ugly truth about =
college football =E2=80=94 this sport is a beauty contest where decisions o=
n which teams can win the national title are sometimes made as much in a co=
zy hotel boardroom in Grapevine, Texas, as they are on the actual field.

In fact, the CFP principles ( https://collegefootballplayoff.com/sports/201=
6/10/24/selection-committee-protocol ) explicitly allow for the committee t=
o consider =E2=80=9Cother relevant factors such as unavailability of key pl=
ayers=E2=80=9D; in Florida State=E2=80=99s place the committee took Alabama=
, which just knocked off Georgia, the number one team in the country nearly=
 three years running, and Texas, the team that gave Alabama its only loss (=
Texas lost once to Oklahoma). It=E2=80=99s probably going to make for a =E2=
=80=9Cbetter=E2=80=9D set of playoff games, and was certainly an outcome th=
at ESPN, the exclusive CFP broadcasting partner, was rooting for.

At the same time, there is no question that Florida State =E2=80=9Cdeserved=
=E2=80=9D it, at least if the regular season is supposed to mean anything: =
they beat an SEC team in non-conference play (LSU), the ACC beat the SEC in=
 aggregate, and that=E2=80=99s above-and-beyond the fact that it is unprece=
dented for a Power 5 champion to go undefeated and not make the CFP; indeed=
, the CFP has on several occasions included non-Power 5 teams in large part=
 because they did go undefeated, and in college football the regular season=
 is supposed to matter.

Then again, this entire debate will be moot next year, because the CFP is e=
xpanding from 4 teams to 12. The Athletic article notes in its conclusion:

There are plenty of people who are against the expansion of the field to 12=
 because of the sanctity of the regular season. But if the games in the reg=
ular season aren=E2=80=99t going to matter when it comes to picking the fin=
al four, then there are no consequences for expanding to 12. The regular se=
ason didn=E2=80=99t decide who made it this year. Thirteen people did. The =
games mattered. The results didn=E2=80=99t.

This conclusion was written in a tiff about the committee=E2=80=99s choice,=
 but it is in fact getting at something that I think is structural (and why=
 I think this is worth commenting on in Stratechery). Specifically, in a wo=
rld of abundance, events matter more than inventory.

Events Over Inventory
---------------------

When it comes to this year, I=E2=80=99m not going to speak for the committe=
e, but certainly ESPN wants what it believes will be more competitive games=
 for the playoffs, even if that means that the regular season is diminished=
; in the long run a 12-team playoff will both mean more teams have a chance=
 and that every regular season game has less life-and-death importance =E2=
=80=94 the payoff will be four rounds of playoffs on national TV, worth a p=
otential $2 billion ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-09-14/es=
pn-says-it-s-flexible-on-expanded-college-football-playoffs ).

That number is aspirational, to be sure, but it is notable that college foo=
tball has by-and-large scored the big increases in rights fees that entitie=
s like the NBA also aspire to, and seem increasingly unlikely to achieve. T=
hat too, though, is a story of events versus inventory: a college football =
playoff may be more of an event than a regular season game, but a game once=
-a-week is more of an event than a league with games on every night.

Preferences used to run in the opposite direction: a decade ago, when cable=
 was still in its heyday, it was important and valuable to have quality con=
tent at high quantity to ensure that there was something good to watch 24/7=
 (and something to talk about on morning and afternoon talk shows). Today, =
though, amidst an absolute explosion in content, both professionally produc=
ed on a myriad of streaming services, and also user-produced on YouTube and=
 social media sites, what matters more is breaking through in a meaningful =
way. Nothing does that like football, and while the NFL is king, college fo=
otball is becoming ever more of a thing ( https://stratechery.com/2022/big-=
ten-blame/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc=
