The NBA is trying to catch up: this week is the final rounds of the =E2=80=
=9CIn-Season Tournament=E2=80=9D, a made-for-TV adaptation of regular seaso=
n games into an event that the NBA hopes fans will tune into and, crucially=
, that networks will bid for. And, speaking of bidding, Amazon is indeed re=
ady to bid for the NBA, but only if playoff games are on the table ( https:=
//www.sportsbusinessjournal.com/Articles/2023/11/20/sports-media.aspx ) : t=
he playoffs are an event, and regular season games are inventory.

NASCAR=E2=80=99s New Deal
-----------------

From the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/business/media/nascar-re=
vs-up-tv-streaming-deals-worth-nearly-8-billion-a15fa530 ) :

Nascar has struck new television and streaming rights deals worth $7.7 bill=
ion with media partners including Amazon, Warner Bros. Discovery and Fox as=
 interest in the sport grows. The value of Nascar=E2=80=99s new seven-year =
deals is 40% higher than its prior arrangements, a person familiar with the=
 situation said. The new deals, which take effect in 2025 and run through 2=
031, highlight the wide range of entertainment companies embracing motorspo=
rt and the growing popularity of streaming as a way consumers watch races.

Nascar forged new deals with Warner Bros. Discovery=E2=80=99s TNT cable net=
work and Max streaming service, Comcast=E2=80=99s NBC Sports, Fox and Nexst=
ar=E2=80=99s CW Network. Fox and NBC will carry fewer races than they had i=
n the previous deal. The races that they are no longer carrying will be spl=
it between Amazon Prime Video as well as TNT and Max.

The 40% increase is in some respects impressive given how focused tradition=
al networks are on profitability; it=E2=80=99s also less than the 50% incre=
ase NASCAR secured a decade ago. What seems to have made the numbers work i=
s that the traditional networks have fewer races, and the streaming service=
s more. What I think is notable is the timing; from Sports Business Journal=
 ( https://www.sportsbusinessjournal.com/Articles/2023/11/29/nascar-media-r=
ights-fox-sports-nbc-warner-bros-discovery-amazon.aspx ) :

As part of the new deals, Fox will get 14 Cup Series races annually in the =
first portion of the season and including the Daytona 500. After Fox carrie=
s its 14 events, Amazon=E2=80=99s Prime Video will stream five events, mark=
ing the first time that NASCAR=E2=80=99s premier events will be exclusively=
 streamed. Warner Bros. Discovery will take over after Amazon=E2=80=99s rac=
es and carry the next five, which will be simulcast on both TNT and the B/R=
 Sports tier on the Max streaming service. NBC Sports will complete the sea=
son with the final 14 races.

The timing for Fox and NBC are similar to the current deal: Fox has races i=
n the spring, but not in the fall when it has football on Sundays; NBC carr=
ies races in the fall as a lead-up to its Sunday night football games. That=
 leaves the summer for streaming, and I don=E2=80=99t think that=E2=80=99s =
an accident.

The key difference between streaming and linear TV is that the former is tr=
ivially canceled: that means it is important to have compelling events ever=
y month. At the same time, because streaming services are not linear networ=
ks, they don=E2=80=99t need to worry about filling inventory. That makes so=
mething like NASCAR ideal: there is an event once a week that makes the sub=
scription worth seeking out for some number of fans, who are likely also in=
terested in events like Amazon=E2=80=99s Thursday night football package, o=
r Discovery Warner Bros. NBA games. The goal for for both services is to ke=
ep fans year round: it=E2=80=99s always cheaper to keep a subscriber than t=
o try and re-acquire one that has churned.

In other words, this is another structural force pushing for events over in=
ventory. Streaming services want to have content that generates a fear of m=
issing out, and sports that are built around appointment viewing are better=
 placed to accomplish that than sports that simply fill up time.

